Brexit, and then what?
NEW YORK – It will take a lot of time for the United Kingdom, Europe, and the entire world to digest the implications of the referendum on the "Brexit" led by the United Kingdom.
The most profound consequences will, of course, depend on the response of the European Union regarding the United Kingdom's withdrawal.
Most people first thought that the EU would not "cut the branch it was sitting on": after all, an amicable divorce seems to be in the interest of all.
But the divorce – as often happens – may become complicated.
The commercial and economic integration benefits between the United Kingdom and the EU are reciprocal, and if the EU were to take seriously its conviction that more economic integration is desirable, its leaders would seek to ensure that the links remain as tight as possible given the circumstances.
However, Jean-Claude Juncker, the architect of massive tax avoidance strategies in favor of companies in Luxembourg and now the President of the European Commission, seems to adopt a hard line: "Out means out," he declared.
This instinctive reaction may be understandable, given that Juncker could be seen as the one who presided over the first step of the dissolution of the EU.
He argues that in order to deter other countries from leaving, the EU must accept no compromise, offering the United Kingdom hardly more than what the World Trade Organization agreements guarantee to it.
In other words, Europe should not be kept united by the benefits it offers its members, which far exceed its costs.
The economic prosperity, the sense of solidarity, and the pride of being a European are not enough, according to Juncker.
No, Europe must be maintained by threats, intimidation, and fear.
This position does not take into account a lesson that appears clearly, both in the vote in favor of Brexit and in the primary elections of the Republican Party in the United States: a large part of the population has suffered greatly in recent times.
The neoliberal agenda of the last four decades may have been good for the top 1%, but not for the rest of the population.
I had long predicted that this stagnation would eventually have political consequences.
This day has finally arrived.
On both sides of the Atlantic, citizens consider that trade agreements are the source of their misfortunes.
Although this is an excessive simplification, it is understandable.
Today's trade agreements are negotiated in secret, ensuring good representation of corporate interests but complete exclusion of ordinary citizens or workers.
Without surprise, the results have been one-way: the workers' negotiation position has weakened further, thus aggravating the effects of the laws that reduce the weight of unions and employees' rights.
Although trade agreements have played a role in creating these inequalities, many other factors have contributed to tipping the political balance in favor of capital.
For example, intellectual property rules have increased the power of pharmaceutical companies to raise prices.
However, any increase in the market power of companies implies a de facto decline in real wages – an increase in inequalities that has become a characteristic of most advanced countries today.
In many sectors, industrial concentration is increasing – along with market power.
The effects of stagnation and the decline in real wages have been added to those of austerity, which have threatened cuts in public services relied upon by many low and middle-income workers.
The economic uncertainty that has resulted for workers, when combined with migration, has created a toxic mix.
Many refugees are victims of the wars and oppression to which the West has contributed.
Providing aid is a moral responsibility for everyone, but especially for the former colonial powers.
And yet, although many would probably deny it, an increase in the offer of low-skilled labor – as long as we are in the presence of normal negative slope demand curves – leads to a decrease in equilibrium wages.
And when wages cannot fall, unemployment increases.
This is especially worrying in countries where poor economic management has already led to a high level of unemployment.
Europe, particularly the eurozone, has been very poorly managed over the last few decades to the point where its average unemployment rate is now in the double digits.
Unrestricted migration in Europe means that countries that have successfully reduced unemployment will ultimately end up hosting more refugees than their fair share.
Workers in these countries bear the cost of depressed wages and higher unemployment, while employers benefit from a better workforce.
The burden of refugees, as no surprise, is borne by those least able to bear it.
Of course, there is a lot of talk about the net benefits of immigration.
For a country offering a low level of guaranteed benefits – social protection, education, healthcare, etc. – to all its citizens, this may be the case.
But, for countries that provide a decent social safety net, the opposite is true.
The result of all this downward pressure on wages and the compressions in public services has been the evisceration of the middle class, with similar consequences on both sides of the Atlantic.
Middle-class and working-class households did not benefit from economic growth.
They understand that banks caused the 2008 crisis; but they then saw billions going towards saving the banks, and insignificant amounts to save their homes and jobs.
While the real median income (adjusted for inflation) for a full-time male worker in the United States is lower than it was four decades ago, the electorate's anger should not come as a surprise.
Moreover, politicians who promised change have not met expectations.
Ordinary citizens knew the system was unfair, but they began to see it as even more rigged than they had imagined, losing the little confidence they still had in the traditional politicians' ability or willingness to correct it.
This is also understandable: the new politicians shared the perspectives of those who promised that globalization would be beneficial to all.
However, a vote of anger does not solve the problems, and may indeed lead to a political and economic situation that is even worse.
The same is true if one responds to a vote with anger.
Forgetting the past is a basic principle in economics.
On both sides of the Channel, politics must now seek to understand how, in a democracy, the political establishment was able to do so little to respond to the concerns of many citizens.
Each government of the EU must now consider the improvement of the well-being of ordinary citizens as its main objective.
MORE neoliberal ideology will not help.
And we should stop confusing means and ends: for example, free trade, if well managed, could bring about a greater shared prosperity; but if badly managed, it will certainly reduce the standard of living of many – possibly the majority – of citizens.
There are alternatives to the current neoliberal arrangements that could create shared prosperity, just as there are alternatives – like the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership with the EU proposed by US President Barack Obama – that would cause a lot more harm.
The challenge today is to learn from the past, so as to adopt the first and avoid the second.
